<div id="comment_status_64482597" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64482597" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64482597" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64482597" name="comment_link_64482597" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23327433&amp;cid=64482597" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64482597)" >Re:How about...no?</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64482597" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64482597); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Luckyo">Luckyo</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Luckyo">( 1726890 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64482597">		
		on Sunday May 19, 2024 @07:57AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23327433&amp;cid=64482597">#64482597</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64482597"><p>It gets worse. Most people don't buy new cars, but used cars. Before amount of distance car travelled combined with age was a very good indicator on how much life there's left in a vehicle.</p><p>Modern electrics are built on the IT model instead. Make resale as hard as possible ("rented rather than bought" amenities mostly don't transfer to new owner, unknown battery wear, etc) because manufacturer doesn't make money on resales. Well, turns out that doesn't actually work in a good as high value as a car. Most people who buy new usually resell to fund the next car. They can't resell or resell at a huge loss, so they go and buy something else.</p><p>So what is happening is that not only are sales peaking and seem to have started to dip in many places even when exceptionally punitive regimes are placed on everything but EVs, but used ones have problems selling at all beyond certain age that is much lower than that of ICEs, and generally have a much greater value loss over time compared to ICE vehicles. Math makes sense, you start with a higher price, and you end up with car that has negative value because battery is worn out and more expensive than the rest of the car much faster than you need to swap something major like an engine in a typical ICE. Which will still be cheaper than battery swap.</p><p>But there's also the aspect that for many political apparatchiks, stated goal isn't transition to EVs, but degrowth. But that's another story.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64482597">
