			<h4><a id="comment_link_64482677" name="comment_link_64482677" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23327433&amp;cid=64482677" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64482677)" >These policies aren't just about clean EVs</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64482677" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64482677); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Tony+Isaac">Tony Isaac</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Tony+Isaac">( 1301187 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64482677"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64482677"><p>For example, the EV tax credit rules <a href="https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions/credits-for-new-clean-vehicles-purchased-in-2023-or-after" title="irs.gov">https://www.irs.gov/credits-de...</a> [irs.gov] exclude vehicles over a certain weight, and over a certain price, and if your income is too high, you don't qualify, and the vehicle must be assembled in the US. There are a bunch of other rules that have nothing to do with the desire to transition to "clean EVs." If I'm a vehicle manufacturer, why shouldn't I be able to protest some of these provisions, without being labeled "anti-EV"?</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64482677">

